04799nam a22007335i 9780801456244DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014562447 a10.7591/97808014562442doi  a(DE-B1597)496375  a(OCoLC)908447712  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJZ6385b.T36 2015eb 7aPOL0100002bisacsh04a355.022231 aTarrow, Sidney, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWar, States, and Contention :bA Comparative Historical Study /cSidney Tarrow. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b11 tables, 15 charts, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures and Maps -- tTables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. 1. Studying War, States, And Contention -- tPart I. War and Movements in the Building of New States -- t2. A Movement-State Goes to War -- t3. A Movement Makes War -- t4. A War Makes Movements -- tPart II. Endless Wars -- t5. From Statist Wars to Composite Conflicts -- t6. Wars at Home, 1917–1975 -- t7. The War at Home, 2001–2013 -- t8. The American State of Terror -- t9. Contesting Hegemony -- tPart III. Internationalization and the New World of Contention -- t10. The Dark Side Of Internationalism -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the last two decades, Sidney Tarrow has explored "contentious politics"—disruptions of the settled political order caused by social movements. These disruptions range from strikes and street protests to riots and civil disobedience to revolution. In War, States, and Contention, Tarrow shows how such movements sometimes trigger, animate, and guide the course of war and how they sometimes rise during war and in war's wake to change regimes or even overthrow states. Tarrow draws on evidence from historical and contemporary cases, including revolutionary France, the United States from the Civil War to the anti–Vietnam War movement, Italy after World War I, and the United States during the decade following 9/11.In the twenty-first century, movements are becoming transnational, and globalization and internationalization are moving war beyond conflict between states. The radically new phenomenon is not that movements make war against states but that states make war against movements. Tarrow finds this an especially troublesome development in recent U.S. history. He argues that that the United States is in danger of abandoning the devotion to rights it had expanded through two centuries of struggle and that Americans are now institutionalizing as a "new normal" the abuse of rights in the name of national security. He expands this hypothesis to the global level through what he calls "the international state of emergency."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPolitics and war. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aWar on Terrorism, 2001-2009xPolitical aspectszUnited States. 4aMilitary History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145624440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801456244423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801456244/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyte